tasks.content: In this part of the course, we will focus on creating and adding an editable layer to our application. The goal is to showcase the capabilities of the Experience Builder app. In our example, we'll design a module intended for users planning new ski slopes. Of course, you can adapt this concept to your own industry â€” the key idea is to enable interactive element editing directly within the Experience Builder application.
In this section, we will focus directly on layer editing, while in the next part I will show you how to use the Table widget for this purpose.

data:image/png;base64,

Go to ArcGIS Online and open the "Content" (1) tab. Click on "New Item" (2) to begin creating a new layer. You can also follow all these steps in the video: Lecture: Creating a new layer in ArcGIS Online.

data:image/png;base64,

data:image/png;base64,

Select "Feature Layer" (3) to create a new layer. Then choose "Select an existing feature layer" (4), since we want to copy the table from an existing layer. Move to the next step by clicking "Next" (5).

data:image/png;base64,

data:image/png;base64,
Select "Les3Vallees_separate" (6), as we want to copy the table structure from this service, then click "Next" (7).

After clicking, youâ€™ll see the layers available within this service. Click "Deselect all" (8) to uncheck all layers, then select "T5_Ski_Slopes" (9) or any layer that contains information about "Ski_Slopes". Finally, click "Next" (10) to proceed.

data:image/png;base64,

data:image/png;base64,
On the next screen, leave the default settings and click "Next" (11). In the final step, name the layer "Designed Ski Slopes" (12) and click "Save" (13).

This way, weâ€™ve created the layer in the ArcGIS Online environment. Now, we will set it to be editable, so users with the appropriate permissions can edit the layer in the Experience Builder application.

data:image/png;base64,

data:image/png;base64,

data:image/png;base64,
Go to the "Data" tab to make sure the table structure was copied correctly and includes all the necessary fields.
Everything looks correct, but note that our table is named "T5_Ski_Slopes" (15).
To change this, go back to the "Overview" tab (16) and click on the "T5_Ski_Slopes" layer (17).

data:image/png;base64,

data:image/png;base64,

data:image/png;base64,
To change the name from "T5_Ski_Slopes" to "DSS" (short for Designed Ski Slopes), click the pencil icon (18) next to the layer name.
Then, change the name (19) to "DSS" and save the changes by clicking "Save" (20).
If everything went as planned, after clicking "Save" you should see the result as shown in the screenshot (21).

data:image/png;base64,

data:image/png;base64,

data:image/png;base64,

data:image/png;base64,
Now, search your content for the WebMap named "XBLD_WebMap_Separate" (22). We will add the layer we just created to this map.
Select "Open in Map Viewer" (23) to open the WebMap.
Next, click the plus icon and select "Browse layers" (24) to find the layer named "Designed Ski Slopes". Once you locate it, click "+ Add" (25).

data:image/png;base64,

data:image/png;base64,

data:image/png;base64,
The layer is now added to the WebMap. In the next step, weâ€™ll change its style â€” setting it to red (project color) with a dashed line, to clearly indicate it's a planned feature.
To do this, select the "Designed Ski Slopes" layer in the "Layers" panel, then choose "Edit Layer Style" (26).
Next, select "Style options" (27), change the line color to red (#ff0000), and set the line style to dashed (29). Once finished, click "Done" (30) to save the changes.

data:image/png;base64,
In the final step, save your WebMap by clicking "Save" (31).

In the next section, weâ€™ll learn how to make our layer editable, as well as how to configure the edit widget so users can interactively make changes to the layer in the Experience Builder application.
In this part of the course, we learned how to create a new layer and add it to a WebMap by reusing the table structure from an existing layer.
